function.arguments:
{"content": "{
 "dialogue": [
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_00",
   "text": "Welcome to the Rational Reminder Podcast. We're joined by Dr. Charles Chafin, whose work bridges psychology and financial planning. We're also excited to share that we've partnered with his company Money and Risk Inventory for a new psychometric risk profiling tool.",
   "emo_text": "Engaging and informative",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_000", "seg_0004"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_01",
   "text": "Yeah, and we're making a public version of their questionnaire available to listeners. It's a solid evidence-based risk tolerance assessment that also explores financial psychology.",
   "emo_text": "Enthusiastic",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_0001"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Psychology plays a huge role—it explains why and how clients behave with money. It bridges the gap between technical advice and real-world behavior.",
   "emo_text": "Thoughtful",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_0007"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Cognitive biases and heuristics are shortcuts that create systematic errors like overconfidence or loss aversion. They get in the way of rational thinking, especially with market noise and FOMO.",
   "emo_text": "Explanatory",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00015"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_00",
   "text": "I think about FOMO and risk tolerance: someone rationally assessing risk considers the full distribution of outcomes, but FOMO focuses only on the right tail, making them think they can take more risk.",
   "emo_text": "Analytical",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00016"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Our environment shapes our financial psychology. We can create friction for behaviors we want to avoid and eliminate friction for those aligned with our goals.",
   "emo_text": "Insightful",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00023"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Money scripts are unconscious beliefs about money that form early in life. Understanding them helps identify potential barriers to financial goals.",
   "emo_text": "Educational",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00035"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Financial risk tolerance is our emotional behavioral response to uncertainty. It's about willingness to endure volatility for potential long-term gain.",
   "emo_text": "Clear",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00059"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_01",
   "text": "How should we combine risk profiles for a couple with materially different risk tolerances?",
   "emo_text": "Curious",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00068"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Dialogue and shared frameworks are critical. Making the abstract concrete can help manage differences and prevent power struggles.",
   "emo_text": "Practical",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00069"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Psychometric tools assess attitudes and beliefs, while revealed preference infers tolerance from past behaviors. Psychometrics give a more complete picture.",
   "emo_text": "Authoritative",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00071"]
 },
 {
   "speaker": "SPEAKER_02",
   "text": "Success, to me, is about alignment and impact. Money is a tool to get there, but meaning comes from having people rely on you and making your actions matter.",
   "emo_text": "Reflective",
   "emo_alpha": 0.6,
   "source_segment_ids": ["seg_00083"]
 }
 ]
}", "mode": "overwrite"}

